<main id="main">

  <h1 id="title">Langston Hughes</h1>

  <p>A trailblazer for the Harlem Renaissance, pioneer of jazz poetry and prolific social activist for young black artists.</p>

  <figure id="img-div">

    <img id="image" src="https://www.biography.com/.image/ar_16:9%2Cc_fill%2Ccs_srgb%2Cfl_progressive%2Cq_auto:good%2Cw_1200/MTYxMDQ2MzI1NTAzMjA2OTE0/american-poet-and-writer-langston-hughes-1902---1967-photo-by-hulton-archivegetty-images.jpg" alt="Langston Hughes poses for a news article" />

    <figcaption id="img-caption">Renowned poet and social activist, Langston Hughes, smiles for a camera while at his desk.
    </figcaption>

  </figure>

  <section id="tribute-info">

    <h3 id="headline">Timeline of Langston Hughes' life.</h3>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>February 1, 1901</strong>: James Mercer Langston Hughes was born in Joplin, Missouri</li>

      <li><strong>1902-early 1920s</strong>: Hughes' father leaves shortly after his birth. He spends the next several years moving around the Midwest with his mother.</li>
      <li><strong>1921</strong>: The official NAACP magazine---<em>The Crisis</em>---publishes "The Negro Speaks of Rivers".</li>

      <li><strong>1923</strong>: Inlisted in the US Navy and served aboard the <em>S.S. Malone </em>to South Africa and Europe. His poem "My People" is published in <em>The Crisis</em></li>

      <li><strong>1924</strong>: Hughes returns to the US.</li>
      <li><strong>1925</strong>: Left his job at the Association for the Study of African American Life and History to work as a busboy at the Wardman Park Hotel citing that his job demanded too much of his time leaving none for writing.</li>
      <li><strong>1926</strong>: Enrolls at Lincoln University in Chester County, Pennsylvania.</li>
      <li><strong>1926</strong>: His manifesto "The Negro Artist and the Racial Mountain" is published in <em>The Nation</em></li>
      <li><strong>1929</strong>: Graduated Lincoln University with a Bachelors of Arts degree.</li>
      <li><strong>1930</strong>: Moves to Harlem. His first novel <em>Not Without Laughter</em> is published.</li>
      <li><strong>1931</strong>: Formed the "New York Suitcase Theater". Created the Golden Stair Press showcasing Hughes' written works and Printess Taylor's artwork.</li>
      <li><strong>1932</strong>: Issued The Scottsboro Limited to shed light on the Scottsboro Boys trial. Helped produce a Soviet film called "Negro Life".</li>
      <li><strong>1934</strong>: His first collection of short stories <em>The Ways of White People</em>.</li>
      <li><strong>1935</strong>: Recieved a Guggenheim Fellowship. Co-wrote the screenplay <em>Way Down South</em>.</li>
      <li><strong>1941</strong>: Founded <em>The Skyloft Players</em>.</li>
      <li><strong>1943</strong>: Wrote a column for the <em>Chicago</em> Defender; which ran for 20 years.</li>
      <li><strong>1947</strong>: He taught at Atlanta College</li>
      <li><strong>1949</strong>: He served as a guest lecturer at the University of Chicago Laboratory Schools.</li>
      <li><strong>1940s-1950s</strong>: He wrote novels, short stories, plays, poetry, operas, essays, and works for children.</li>
      <li><strong>1960s</strong>: Hughes frequently advocated for the young black writers. As the Black Power movement gained momentum, he understood their view points but thought they were too angry in their writings.</li>
      <li><strong>1967</strong>: James Mercer Langston Hughes passed away due to surgery complications from prostate cancer. He was 66 years old.</li>
      <li><strong>1967</strong>: Posthumusly published, <em>Panther and the Lash</em>, intended to express "solidarity with these writers, but with more skill and devoid of the most virulent anger and racial chauvinism some showed toward whites."</li>
    </ul>
    <hr>
    <h4>
      To read even more about Langston Hughes' contributions to African American culture, activism and accomplishments, please visit his <a id="tribute-link" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Langston_Hughes" target="_blank">Wikipedia Page</a>.
    </h4>
